I.    Introduction

A Risk Management Program has been implemented at the Rose Packing Company, Inc. (Rose Packing), Chicago facility, for the reduction of accidental releases of hazardous materials. This updated, Risk Management Plan (RMP) has been prepared to reflect changes made to the system and the resulting addition of ammonia to the system. The RMP summarizes the management, administrative, procedural, and technological controls that work together to minimize the risk to site personnel, contractors, visitors, and the community and environment at large of hazardous chemical releases. The Risk Management Plan (RMP) is organized to correspond with specific U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) RMP, Program 3 of 40 CFR 68, definitions and requirements of Subpart G, including: 

?    Introduction;

?    Rose Packing's policies to protect health, environment, and safety;

?    Facility identification and regulated substances covered processes;

?    Hazard Assessment;

?    Prevention Program;

?    Five-Year Accident History;

?    Emergency Response Plan; 

?    Emergency Communications;

?    Spill Reporting / Environmental Release Procedures;

?    Planned changes to improve safety; and

?    Management Program



II.    Rose Packing's Policies To Protect Health, Environment, and Safety

Risk management and safety are important concerns at Rose Packing; this RMP formalizes and documents these activities. Rose Packing is committed to conducting its operations in a safe and responsible manner and to reducing risks to human health and to the environment. It is Rose Packing's policy to comply with all applicable federal, state, and local rules and regulations.



